SIMPLE: friendly
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Friendly
<hw>Friend"ly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>fre⟦eacute⟧ndl⟦imac⟧ce</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the
temper and disposition of a friend; disposed to promote the good of
another; kind; favorable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Appropriate to, or implying, friendship; befitting
friends; amicable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In <qex>friendly</qex> relations with his moderate opponents.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Not hostile; <as>as, a <ex>friendly</ex> power or
state</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Promoting the good of any person; favorable;
propitious; serviceable; <as>as, a <ex>friendly</ex> breeze or
gale</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On the first <qex>friendly</qex> bank he throws him down.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Amicable; kind; conciliatory; propitious;
favorable. See <er>Amicable</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Friendly</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Friendly
<hw>Friend"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In the manner of friends;
amicably; like friends.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In whom all graces that can perfect beauty⟦br⟧
Are <qex>friendly</qex> met.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Friendly</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Friendly
<hw>Friend"ly</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A friendly person; --
usually applied to natives friendly to foreign settlers or
invaders.</def></p>

<p><q>These were speedily routed by the <qex>friendlies</qex>, who
attacked the small force before them in fine style.</q> <rj><qau>E. N.
Bennett.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A member of one's own military
forces, or of allied forces.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>friendly fire</ent>⟦br⟧
